'''Shashank Arora''' (born 21 February 1989)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Shashank-Arora|title=Shashank Arora: Movies, Photos, Videos, News, Biography & Birthday {{!}} eTimes|website=timesofindia.indiatimes.com|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> is an [[India|Indian]] actor, writer and musician. He is known for his roles in [[Titli (2014 film)|Titli]], [[Brahman Naman]],  and [[Made in Heaven (TV series)|Made in Heaven]]. His films have premiered and competed at festivals around the world including Cannes, Sundance, Locarno, Berlin, Toronto and Venice.

==Early life and education==
Born Shashank 'Sunny' Arora on 21 February 1989, Shashank was interested in music and theatre from a young age. While in Canada, he briefly joined a street theatre group formed by human rights activists. In late 2008, he moved to Mumbai where he studied acting for two years and began his career as an actor.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}

Arora was born in New Delhi.<ref name="PuneInterview">{{Cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/others/sunday-read/Small-Talk-Shashanks-redemption/articleshow/54633740.cms|title=Small Talk: Shashank’s redemption|last=Guha|first=Kunal|website=Pune Mirror|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> His parents are graphic designers. He was part of plays in school as well. He was inspired by Francis Ford Coppola and Saeed Mirza’s cinema as a child.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/seeking-truth/article23811024.ece|title=Working with Nawaz was wonderful, says Shashank Arora on 'Manto'|last=Khan|first=Atif|date=2018-05-08|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-06-09|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> In order to pursue a career in music, Arora went to Canada to do his graduation in filmmaking, with music as a minor subject. After finishing his degree, he came back to Mumbai but was unable to find work, hence he went back to studying. He credits his professor Robert Reece for everything he knows.<ref name="PuneInterview"/> He later joined Whistling Woods and [[Film and Television Institute of India]] as a teacher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.societymag.co.in/article/features/“We-are-in-the-dark-ages-of-cinema”-Shashank-Arora/12218|title=“We are in the dark ages of cinema” - Shashank Arora|last=Paul|first=Rahul|date=2018-07-17|website=Stardust|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> He also worked under casting director Saher Latif.<ref name="PuneInterview"/>

==Career==
Arora first appeared as a supporting character in a movie titled ''Myoho'' (2012), as Ranjit.<ref name="Myoho">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/myoho-11260/cast-crew|title=Myoho (2012) Cast - Actor, Actress, Director, Producer, Music Director|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref><ref name="MultiStarrer">{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shashank-arora-feels-comfortable-doing-multi-starrers-4368487/|title=Shashank Arora feels comfortable doing multi-starrers|date=2016-11-10|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-US}}</ref> His first major role was the titular role in the critically acclaimed movie '' [[Titli (2014 film)|Titli]]''(2014), produced by [[Yash Raj Films]].<ref name="Titli HT">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/titli-review-this-is-the-best-hindi-film-of-the-year-so-far/story-upwdbFVhPQ95hrOFRwQM2L.html|title=Titli review: This is the best Hindi film of the year so far|date=2015-10-30|first=Rohit|last=Vats|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref>  The film competed at the 2014 [[Cannes Film Festival]]. He was also nominated at Filmfare, Stardust and Zee Cine awards as best newcomer for his role in Titli the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/stardust-awards-badlapur-bajrangi-bhaijaan-tanu-weds-manu-returns-others-nominated-658169|title=Stardust awards: Badlapur, Bajrangi Bhaijaan, Tanu Weds Manu Returns, others nominated; complete list of nominations|last=IBTimes|date=2015-12-05|website=International Business Times, India Edition|language=english|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref><ref name="StardustNom">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/nominations-for-stardust-awards-2015/|title=Nominations for Stardust Awards 2015 - Bollywood Hungama|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|date=2015-12-15|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> In 2016, he played Naman in the movie [[Brahman Naman]]. Rohan Naahar of Hindustan Times said that "..He makes the really odd choice to play his character like that posh monkey from the Madagascar movies, which just adds to the weirdness.."<ref name="BrahmanReview">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/brahman-naman-review-netflix-s-1st-indian-film-is-a-perverted-american-pie/story-aQMjTP6Ry2LR1DQqdtKjfK.html|first=Rohan|last=Naahar|title=Brahman Naman review: Netflix’s 1st Indian film is a perverted American Pie|date=2016-07-08|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref>  Next, he played the role of Uday, a bass player in the movie ''[[Rock On 2]]'' in the same year.<ref name="huffpostRockon">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/09/02/rock-on-2-poster-revealed_a_21464827/|title='Rock On!! 2' Poster Released, Shraddha Kapoor, Shashank Arora Join The Band|date=2016-09-03|website=HuffPost India|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref><ref name="MumbaiRockOn">{{Cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-review/rock-on-2-review-the-farhan-akhtar-film-is-a-largely-tiresome-affair/articleshow/55370871.cms|title='Rock On 2' review: The Farhan Akhtar film is a largely tiresome affair|last=Guha|first=Kunal |website=Mumbai Mirror|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> 

In 2017, he portrayed the role of Bicky, a drug peddler in the movie ''Zoo''.<ref name="Zoo">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/201017/making-movies-on-the-phone-1.html|title=This film shot completely on iPhone was screened at the MAMI Film Festival|last=Basu|first=Dyuti|date=2017-10-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> For preparation for the role , Arora tried to sell narcotics and was arrested for the same.<ref name="MintInterview">{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/HhwWq1eUWzgjEzYFb7MVtN/Shashank-Arora-Portrait-of-a-young-actor.html|title=Shashank Arora: Portrait of a young actor|last=Ghosh|first=Sankhayan|date=2017-11-17|work=livemint|access-date=2017-12-08}}</ref> He was seen next as Dhruv in the critically acclaimed movie ''[[Lipstick Under My Burkha]]''(2017).<ref name="Lipstick">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/n4GrZtbyVSyYliEM0M7BeP/Film-Review-Lipstick-Under-My-Burkha.html|title=Film Review: Lipstick Under My Burkha|last=Bhatia|first=Uday|date=2017-07-21|website=livemint|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> He was also seen in ''[[The Song of Scorpions]]'' as Munna,in the same year.<ref name="SongsScorpion">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/song-scorpions-1027941|title='The Song of Scorpions': Film Review {{!}} Locarno 2017|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/the-song-of-scorpions-review-1202523693/|title=Film Review: ‘The Song of Scorpions’|last=Weissberg|first=Jay|last2=Weissberg|first2=Jay|date=2017-08-11|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> Later,he was seen portraying the titular character in the web series ''Gangster Newton''.<ref name="newton">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/070317/shashank-arora-will-soon-be-seen-in-scientific-gangster-comedy-gangster-newton.html|title=Shashank Arora will soon be seen in scientific gangster comedy- Gangster Newton|date=2017-03-07|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> Following that, Arora also essayed the role of Shaad Amritsari in Nandita Das' ''[[Manto (2018 film)|Manto]]'' in 2018. The film was Shashank's second in the Un Certain Regard category at the prestigious Cannes Film Festival, making him and Nawazuddin Siddiqui the first Indian actors to have two films in Un Certain Regard at Cannes. <ref name="Manto">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shashank-arora-manto-cannes-film-festival-5176332/|title=Shashank Arora: There’s no better time than now for Nandita Das to have made Manto|date=2018-05-14|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> In the same year, he appeared in the short films, ''the Listener'', directed by Tarun Judega, ''Letters'' directed by Nitin Shingal and ''Others'' directed by Sachin Shinde.<ref name="TheListener">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/bollywood-actor-kumud-mishra-stars-in-tarun-dudeja-s-short/article_fd6c1c42-4666-11e8-aa0e-0b9813ed8913.html|title=Bollywood Actor Kumud Mishra Stars in Tarun Dudeja's Short Film ‘Listener’: Watch|last=Vijayakar|first=R. M.|website=India West|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name="Letters">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riff.it/scheda-film/|title=Scheda Film|website=RIFF|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name="others">{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/socially-relevant-film-others-released-on-sony-liv-app-118102601110_1.html|title=Socially relevant film 'Others' released on Sony Liv App|last=ANI|date=2018-10-26|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2019, Arora was seen in the Amazon Prime series ′'[[Made in Heaven (TV series)|Made In Heaven]]′' as Kabir Basrai, a photographer.<ref name="Heaven">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/made-in-heaven-review-this-sumptuous-take-on-the-big-fat-indian-wedding-has-a-strong-emotional-core-6196291.html|title=Made in Heaven review: This sumptuous take on the big fat Indian wedding has a strong emotional core- Entertainment News, Firstpost|date=2019-03-08|website=Firstpost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> He was also seen  portraying the role of [[Salman Khan]]'s younger brother, Chote in [[Bharat (film)|Bharat]].<ref name="Bharat">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/salman-khan-bharat-shashank-arora-5209048/|title=Exclusive: Shashank Arora to play Salman Khan’s brother in Bharat|date=2018-06-08|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> He was also seen in [[Moothon]].<ref name="Moothon">{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/moothon-bollywood-actors-shashank-arora-sobhita-dhulipala-nivin-pauly-film-4685406/|title=Moothon: Bollywood actors Shashank Arora, Sobhita Dhulipala roped in for Nivin Pauly film|date=2017-06-02|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-US}}</ref>

